 To compute \ (\frac{x^6-16x^3+64}{x^3-8}\) when \(x=6\), let''s first factorize the numerator and denominator. Notice that the denominator can be factored using the difference of cubes formula \(x^3-8 = (x-2)(x^2+2x+4)\). Similarly, the numerator \(x^6-16x^3+64\) can be rewritten as a perfect square trinomial. 
Express the expression as:
 \[\begin{aligned}
\frac{x^6-16x^3+64}{x^3-8}
&=\frac{(x^3)^2-2·x^3·8+8^2}{x^3-8}\\
&=\frac{(x^3-8)^2}{x^3-8}\\
&=x^3-8 \text{ for }x\neq 2
\end{aligned}
\] So, when \(x=6\), \[ x^3-8=6^3-8=212. \] Therefore, the answer is: \(\boxed{212}\).

